  "text": "The Prometheus TSDB head block enforces series cardinality limits and handles out-of-order/out-of-bounds samples through a coordinated system of components.\n\n## Series Cardinality Limit Enforcement\n\nThe head block series limit is enforced through the **SeriesLifecycleCallback** interface (tsdb/head.go:234), which is called during series creation. The key method is **getOrCreateWithOptionalID** (tsdb/head.go:1844) which calls the PreCreation callback before creating a new series. If this callback returns an error (e.g., due to cardinality limits being exceeded), the series creation is rejected and the error is propagated up to the appender.\n\n## Out-of-Order and Out-of-Bounds Sample Handling\n\nThe TSDB head block handles out-of-order and out-of-bounds samples through a sophisticated pipeline:\n\n### 1. Fast-Path Out-of-Bounds Check (tsdb/head_append_v2.go:127-132)\nWhen out-of-order support is disabled (oooTimeWindow == 0), samples with timestamps before minValidTime are immediately rejected with ErrOutOfBounds. This prevents wasting resources on samples that cannot be inserted.\n\n### 2. Sample Appendability Validation (tsdb/head_append.go)\nThree methods validate whether samples can be appended:\n- **appendable** (line 643): Validates float samples for order and time bounds\n- **appendableHistogram** (line 688): Validates native histogram samples\n- **appendableFloatHistogram** (line 730): Validates float histogram samples\n\nThese methods return:\n- isOOO=false, err=nil: Sample is in-order and can be appended\n- isOOO=true, err=nil: Sample is out-of-order but within the OOO time window\n- isOOO=true, err=ErrTooOldSample: Sample is too old, outside OOO window (OOO enabled)\n- isOOO=false, err=ErrOutOfBounds: Sample is out of bounds (OOO disabled, t < minValidTime)\n- isOOO=false, err=ErrOutOfOrderSample: Sample is out-of-order (OOO disabled, t < headMaxt)\n\n### 3. Sample Insertion into OOO Chunks (tsdb/head_append.go:1799)\nThe **insert** method handles out-of-order samples by inserting them into OOO chunks. When the OOO chunk reaches capacity (oooCapMax), a new OOO chunk is cut and the old one is memory-mapped. The actual insertion into the OOO chunk data structure is delegated to **OOOChunk.Insert** (tsdb/ooo_head.go:37).\n\n### 4. Commit-Time OOO Processing (tsdb/head_append.go:1310-1600)\nThe **commitFloats**, **commitHistograms**, and **commitFloatHistograms** methods process appended samples during commit:\n- In-order samples are appended directly via series.append()\n- Out-of-order samples are inserted via series.insert()\n- Samples that fail appendability checks are tracked and metrics are updated\n- The **handleAppendableError** helper (line 1275) categorizes errors and updates rejection counters\n\n### 5. OOO Chunk Data Structure (tsdb/ooo_head.go)\nThe **OOOChunk** maintains samples in time-ascending order using binary search-based insertion. Duplicate timestamps are rejected, and samples are stored uncompressed for efficient sorting during OOO chunk compaction.\n\n## Error Handling and Metrics\n\nErrors during sample appending are tracked through prometheus metrics:\n- outOfBoundSamples: Fast-path rejections when OOO is disabled\n- outOfOrderSamples: In-order check failures (OOO disabled)\n- tooOldSamples: Out-of-order samples outside the OOO time window\n- outOfOrderSamplesAppended: Successfully inserted OOO samples\n\nThese metrics allow operators to monitor sample ingestion quality and identify configuration issues with scrape intervals or time synchronization."
}

